docs.abstract: There is a precedent for letting states impose work requirements on the poor for medical coverage. It bodes ill for public health.

docs.abstract: President Trump and congressional Republicans are reviving an enduring party view that tying work requirements to antipoverty programs benefits those in need. There’s little evidence that’s so.
docs.snippet: President Trump and congressional Republicans are reviving an enduring party view that tying work requirements to antipoverty programs benefits those in need. There’s little evidence that’s so.
docs.lead_paragraph: There’s something almost eerie about the unwavering nature of the Republican system of belief.

headline.main: G.O.P. Insists Making Poor People Work Lifts Them Up. Where’s the Proof?
headline.print_headline: The G.O.P. Insists That Work Works

docs.abstract: A merger would broaden Goldman’s client base and reduce its reliance on trading. If only watchdogs, customers and the target itself could be won over.
docs.snippet: A merger would broaden Goldman’s client base and reduce its reliance on trading. If only watchdogs, customers and the target itself could be won over.
docs.lead_paragraph: There’s a potentially ideal merger partner for the $104 billion Goldman Sachs. The Wall Street firm’s chief executive, Lloyd C. Blankfein, told shareholders on Tuesday that it was already having some success turning around its stumbling fixed-income, currency and commodities trading unit. But buying $56 billion Bank of New York Mellon could be a better fix — if only the asset-management and custody specialist weren’t in a different league.

headline.main: Here’s an Idea for Goldman: Buy Bank of New York Mellon

docs.abstract: The company said it had taken down 865.8 million posts in the first quarter of 2018, the vast majority of them spam, and 583 million fake accounts. There were limited specifics on what was pulled.
docs.snippet: The company said it had taken down 865.8 million posts in the first quarter of 2018, the vast majority of them spam, and 583 million fake accounts. There were limited specifics on what was pulled.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Facebook has been under pressure for its failure to remove violence, nudity, hate speech and other inflammatory content from its site. Government officials, activists and academics have long pushed the social network to disclose more about how it deals with such posts.

headline.main: Facebook Says It Deleted 865 Million Posts, Mostly Spam

docs.abstract: The investor group that agreed to buy most of the embattled studio’s assets said it had received “disappointing information” that prompted it to call off the deal.
docs.snippet: The investor group that agreed to buy most of the embattled studio’s assets said it had received “disappointing information” that prompted it to call off the deal.
docs.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — The planned sale of the Weinstein Company collapsed yet again on Tuesday, when the investor group that had agreed to purchase the embattled studio said that it had called off the deal after receiving “disappointing information.”

headline.main: Planned Sale of the Weinstein Company Collapses Again
headline.print_headline: Planned Sale of Weinstein Company  Collapses Again as Investors Back Off

docs.abstract: Mr. Pulte was part of a postwar generation of builders who turned a mom-and-pop industry into a giant one traded on the New York Stock Exchange.
docs.snippet: Mr. Pulte was part of a postwar generation of builders who turned a mom-and-pop industry into a giant one traded on the New York Stock Exchange.
docs.lead_paragraph: William Pulte, who built his first house as a teenager and went on to found one of the country’s largest home builders, churning out some 600,000 houses and becoming a billionaire, died on Wednesday at his home in Naples, Fla. He was 85.

headline.main: William Pulte, Pathbreaking Home Builder, Is Dead at 85
headline.print_headline: William Pulte, 85, Is Dead; Pathbreaking Home Builder  Helped Expand Middle Class

docs.abstract: Stephen Schwarzman, the private equity billionaire, offered a Pennsylvania high school $25 million. He wanted his name and likeness all over the school.
docs.snippet: Stephen Schwarzman, the private equity billionaire, offered a Pennsylvania high school $25 million. He wanted his name and likeness all over the school.
docs.lead_paragraph: ABINGTON, Pa. — Stephen A. Schwarzman, the Wall Street billionaire, was prepared to cut a $25 million check to the high school he attended here in the 1960s, to help it pay for a huge renovation project.

headline.main: A Public Outcry Against a Wall Street Titan’s Name on a High School
headline.print_headline: Wall St. Titan  Provokes Fury  At Alma Mater

docs.abstract: The allure of investment options like hedge funds and venture capital remains strong for universities, even though standard stock index funds have outperformed them in the last 10 years.
docs.snippet: The allure of investment options like hedge funds and venture capital remains strong for universities, even though standard stock index funds have outperformed them in the last 10 years.
docs.lead_paragraph: It’s official: Returns for college and university endowments for the 2017 fiscal year are in, and while they averaged a respectable 12.2 percent for the year, over the last decade they have underperformed funds offering a simple 60-40 or 70-30 stock-fixed income allocation.

headline.main: College Endowments Opt for Alternative, and Less Lucrative, Route

docs.abstract: The film and television studio has been struggling in the wake of sexual misconduct allegations against Harvey Weinstein, its co-owner.
docs.snippet: The film and television studio has been struggling in the wake of sexual misconduct allegations against Harvey Weinstein, its co-owner.
docs.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — The Weinstein Company said that it would file for bankruptcy following the collapse of sale talks with an investor group, extending the damage from sexual misconduct allegations against Harvey Weinstein, its co-owner and a onetime force in Hollywood.

headline.main: Weinstein Co. Will File for Bankruptcy After Deal Talks Collapse
headline.print_headline: Weinstein Co. Says It Will File For Bankruptcy As Sale Falters
